1ca0435d-c0ff-4d26-bd08-29f0c568992b.2ecb3278-1f60-4717-bebd-55ce06cd9ea1.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.
1ca0435d-c0ff-4d26-bd08-29f0c568992b.917bc5c2-7623-4ccd-aa69-9dc1a29f007a.description=
This operation adds a flow variable to the local context. The variable is available in the current flow and its child flows.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The name of the flow variable to add.
    myValue - The value to assign to the flow variable.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of "myValue" input field.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.

Note\:
   If a flow variable with the same name already exists, its value will be overwritten.
1ca0435d-c0ff-4d26-bd08-29f0c568992b.98ddc2ea-f004-44d5-bd32-8142e4435c65.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
1ca0435d-c0ff-4d26-bd08-29f0c568992b.a5fb1161-a271-4bcf-8408-36e7f99962de.description=
This operation does not do anything. It can be used to filter flow variables by defining them as inputs and filtering them in the Results tab.

Inputs\:
    field1 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field2 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field3 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field4 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of  "field1" as it was specified at input or when filtered. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
1ca0435d-c0ff-4d26-bd08-29f0c568992b.ad4633e9-09e1-4224-b91f-5d2a54bd3720.description=
This operation takes a reference to JSON (in the form of a string) and runs a specified JSON Path query on it. It returns the results as a JSON Object. 

Inputs\:
    json - The JSON in the form of a string.
    jsonPathQuery - The JSON Path query to run. See details and examples in the Notes section below.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the resulted JSON from the given path.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Notes\:
1.Query syntax\:
JSONPath 		Description
------------                           -------------     
$ 		The root object/element
@ 		The current object/element
. or [] 		Child operator
n/a 		Parent operator
.. 		Recursive descent. JSONPath borrows this syntax from E4X.
* 		Wildcard. All objects/elements regardless of their names.
n/a 		Attribute access. JSON structures do not have attributes.
[] 		Subscript operator. XPath uses it to iterate over element collections and for predicates. In Javascript and JSON it is the native array operator.
[,] 		Union operator in XPath results in a combination of node sets. JSONPath allows alternate names or array indices as a set.
[start\:end\:step] 	Array slice operator borrowed from ES4.
?() 		Applies a filter (script) expression.
() 		Sript expression, using the underlying script engine.

2.Examples\:
The examples below use the following JSON string value\:
{
    store\: {
        book\: [
            {
                category\: reference,
                author\: Nigel Rees,
                title\: Sayings of the Century,
                price\: 8.95
            },
            {
                category\: fiction,
                author\: Evelyn Waugh,
                title\: Sword of Honour,
                price\: 12.99
            },
            {
                category\: fiction,
                author\: Herman Melville,
                title\: Moby Dick,
                isbn\: 0-553-21311-3,
                price\: 8.99
            },
            {
                category\: fiction,
                author\: J. R. R. Tolkien,
                title\: The Lord of the Rings,
                isbn\: 0-395-19395-8,
                price\: 22.99
            }
        ],
    bicycle\: {
            color\: red,
            price\: null
        }    
    },
    expensive\: 10
}

JSONPath 			Result
------------                                                ---------
$.store.book[*].author 		The authors of all books in the store
$...author 			All authors\: ["Nigel Rees","Evelyn Waugh","Herman Melville","J. R. R. Tolkien"]
$.store.* 			All items in store, which are some books and a red bicycle.
$.store..price 		The price of everything in the store
$..book[2] 			The third book
$..book[(@.length-1)] or $..book[-1\:] 	The last book in order
$..book[0,1] or $..book[\:2] 	The first two books
$..book[?(@.isbn)] 		Filter all books with isbn number
$..book[?(@.price<10)] 		Filter all books wholse price is less than 10
$..* 			All Elements in XML document. All members of JSON structure. 
$.store.book[0]		Returns the details of the first book\: reference,Nigel Rees,Sayings of the Century,8.95
$.store.bicycle			Returns the details of the bicycle including null in JSON format\: {"color"\:"red","price"\:null}
